1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1172":"1172",",, Spain":"Spanje"},"en":{"Abt 1148–UNKNOWN":"about 1148–Deceased","1146–1196":"1146–1196","1172–1194":"1172–1194","1174–Male":"1174–Deceased","1148–Female":"1148–Deceased","1148":"1148","1146":"1146","1200":"1200","Abt 1148":"about 1148","1174":"1174","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1172":"1172",",, Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rada","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Delfin, Ernesto, Jose, Lilia, Adelardo, Alipio, Arquimedes, Arturo, Cesar, Cruz, Eladia.","Czech and Slovak: from a short form of any of various Slavic personal names containing the element <i>rad</i> ‘merry, glad’ (from Old Slavic <i>radъ</i>), such as <i>Radoslav</i>, in which the second element means ‘glory’ or ‘famous’.","Hungarian: from the old personal name <i>Rada</i> or <i>Ráda</i>, of Slavic origin (see 1 above and   Rad  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rach","meanings":["German: from Middle High German <i>rach</i> ‘rough, stiff’, a nickname for someone affected by hard work, or a topographic name from the same word in the sense ‘steep, rough’.","Czech, Polish, and Sorbian: from a pet form of the personal names beginning with <i>Ra-</i>, especially Slavic names such as Czech <i>Radoslav</i>, Polish and Sorbian <i>Radosław</i> (see   Rada  )."]},{"name":"Radach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Christoph, Otto, Waltraut.","German: from a short form of any of various Slavic personal names based on Old Slavic <i>radъ</i> ‘merry, glad’ (see   Rada   1).","Americanized form of Czech <b>Radáč</b>: from a pet form of a personal name containing the Slavic element <i>rad</i> ‘merry, glad’ (see   Rada   1)."]},{"name":"Rad","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Ali, Bijan, Abbas, Amad, Masoud, Nader, Nasser, Saeed, Ahmad, Alireza, Amir, Azin.","Iranian: from Persian <i>rād</i> ‘bold, brave’, also ‘skilful, learned’, forming the second part (originally a suffix) of compound names such as <b>Mahdavirad</b> or <b>Mahdavi Rad</b> (see   Mahdavi  ). The surname may also be from the personal name <i>Rād</i>, based on the same word. Compare   Raad   2.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>rād</i>, <i>rāt</i> ‘advice, counsel’."]},{"name":"Radack","meanings":["German: from a Germanized pet form of any of various Slavic personal names based on Old Slavic <i>radъ</i> ‘merry, glad’ (see   Rada   1, compare   Radak  ).","Americanized form of Serbian and Croatian   Radak  .","History: The progenitor of many of the American Radacks was Ephraim Radack, a German from Alt Danzig in the Russian Empire (today Karlivka in Ukraine), a settlement founded by the colonists from Danzig in Prussia (today Gdansk in Poland). He and his family immigrated to SD in the 1870s."]}]},{"name":"Ines","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Agnes  , now also used, usually without the accent, in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodge